AB  - While Industry 4.0 drives demand for adaptive human-robot collaboration, challenges persist in robotic intelligence, computational efficiency, and unstructured-environment adaptability. This study proposes integrating Large Language Models (LLMs) and Vision-Language Models (VLMs) to enhance collaborative assembly systems. LLMs translate natural language into machine-executable commands, simplifying human-robot interaction. VLMs process camera-captured color/depth data to construct perceptual spaces, improving environmental awareness with minimal training data. By combining LLM-generated instructions and VLM-derived spatial insights, the system enables autonomous trajectory planning and optimized motion control. This dual-model framework reduces operational complexity, enhances adaptability to unstructured scenarios, and improves generalization for modern manufacturing's evolving demands. © 2025 Copyright held by the owner/author(s).
