AB  - We demonstrate a novel agentic control architecture for dynamic edge network reconfiguration, featuring a dual - Model Context Protocol (MCP) deployment: one instance at the gNodeB and another at the User Equipment (UE), coordinated via a shared client interface. A large language model (LLM) receives high-level user intent (e.g., "improve video call stability") and constructs a semantic action plan conditioned on real-time context and validated operational constraints. The system enables collaborative reasoning across the UE and RAN components, with human-in-the-loop authorization governing execution. Unlike conventional APIs or policy engines, MCP supports reversibility, semantic validation, and learning from feedback. This demonstration highlights the potential for intent-driven, context-aware, verifiable autonomy in edge wireless systems. © 2025 Copyright held by the owner/author(s).
