AB  - [Objective] To address the challenge of automatically detecting emerging research topics, this study proposes a method that combines graph neural networks and large language models to summarize key information. [Methods] We used the NE-GraphSAGE model, which aggregates both node and edge information, to identify papers more likely to reveal frontier issues in a field. Then, we input these papers into a large language model guided by structured prompts, chain-of-thought prompts, and few-shot learning prompts to detect emerging research topics. Similarity metrics are used to evaluate the detection effectiveness. [Results] Compared to N-GraphSAGE model based on node aggregation and E-GraphSAGE model based on edge aggregation, our new model performed best, achieving an accuracy of 0.839 8. The use of all three prompting techniques improved the LLM’s detection performance; in ChatGPT-4o’s output, the F1 scores for“terms”and“explanations”reached 0.73 and 0.77, respectively. It was also observed that long texts and large numbers of learning examples negatively affected the model’s inference performance. [Limitations] Our study relies solely on paper data as the detection source, which limits the diversity of analytical dimensions. [Conclusions] The proposed automatic detection framework reduces human subjectivity and improves the granularity of topic detection, providing a valuable perspective for achieving“human-AI collaboration”. © 2025 Chinese Academy of Sciences. All rights reserved.
