TI  - Operator-in-the-Loop Multi-Objective Scheduling of Multi-Energy Microgrids via LLM-Guided Reinforcement Learning
PY  - 2025
T2  - IEEE Transactions on Industry Applications
DO  - 10.1109/TIA.2025.3647602
UR  - https://www.scopus.com/inward/record.uri?eid=2-s2.0-105025774667&doi=10.1109%2FTIA.2025.3647602&partnerID=40&md5=cffc5e530e145c5fa492d7bdaad1ea46
AB  - Operating multi-energy microgrids (MEMGs) under uncertain generation and load conditions requires adaptive strategies to balance competing objectives. Traditional multi-objective optimization methods rely on static weight settings, which fail to reflect shifting priorities in real-world environments. In this context, this paper proposes an operator-in-the-loop agentic scheduling framework based on Large Language Model-guided Multi-Objective Soft Actor-Critic (LLM-MOSAC). In this framework, the LLM serves as an intelligent agent generating context-aware weight ranges that are refined via operator feedback and optimized using an entropy-driven evolutionary algorithm. To improve robustness under uncertainty, a State-Adversarial Markov Decision Process (SA-MDP) is developed to introduce perturbations during training, enabling the policy to maintain stable performance in dynamic environments. This collaborative architecture enhances adaptability, reduces manual tuning effort, and improves the interpretability and resilience of the scheduling policy. Simulation results demonstrate that the proposed method enhances MEMG optimization by improving adaptability and robustness, providing an efficient and sustainable solution for multi-energy systems. © 1972-2012 IEEE.
