DO  - 10.1109/ICIRT66379.2025.11216746
UR  - https://www.scopus.com/inward/record.uri?eid=2-s2.0-105025117095&doi=10.1109%2FICIRT66379.2025.11216746&partnerID=40&md5=6f3aa524aa4452fcc5fddf5785d83e12
AB  - Traditional train trajectory evaluation methods suffer from subjectivity, inefficiency, and poor adaptability to dynamic conditions. This study proposes a tuning-free LLM framework that integrates domain knowledge through dynamic prompts and human-in-the-loop feedback, enabling automated code generation for real-time driver assessment. This framework contains three main parts: constraint-driven prompt engineering dynamically generates structured prompts by integrating task semantics and domain knowledge, and a modular code synthesis produces executable code via stepwise generation, separating data processing, feature calculation, and rule application into modular components while embedding domain-specific constraints. Furthermore, a human-in-the-loop optimization workflow is introduced to validate outputs through automated execution and human feedback, refining prompts and code iteratively until convergence. This study bridges LLMs' linguistic capabilities with domain-specific problem-solving, achieving an average of 85.9% consistency with numerical simulations while significantly reducing expert dependency. © 2025 IEEE.
