TI  - LLM AND KNOWLEDGE GRAPH-BASED INTELLIGENT CONTROL FRAMEWORK FOR SMART MANUFACTURING
PY  - 2025
VL  - 2-A
C7  - v02at02a033
DO  - 10.1115/DETC2025-168925
UR  - https://www.scopus.com/inward/record.uri?eid=2-s2.0-105024199732&doi=10.1115%2FDETC2025-168925&partnerID=40&md5=17fb3b61b7628a54327ee6be56b6c228
AB  - The rapid development of large language models (LLMs) and robotics is fundamentally reshaping the manufacturing sector. LLMs have already had a profound impact across multiple fields, such as document management, medical consultation, education, etc. However, the inherent complexity and dynamic nature of manufacturing continue to pose challenges for applying LLMs in robotic control within this domain, particularly in understanding the spatial and logical relationships between different objects. Although fine-tuning can be implemented, it requires a significant amount of time for each iteration and does not support real-time updates, making it unsuitable for industrial applications. To relieve the problem, this paper proposes a novel industrial robot control scheme called the LLM-Knowledge Graph (KG) Powered Intelligent Agent Framework (LKPI). The goal is to fully leverage the external knowledge and logical relationships provided by KG to enhance robotic perception and decision-making in complex production environments, without the need to fine-tune the LLMs. In experimental validation, LKPI demonstrated superior logical reasoning and environmental adaptability in a dynamic and noise-prone pecan processing scenario. Even when the camera could not directly identify the target object, LKPI utilized environmental background information and relationship information stored in the KG to accomplish transportation and navigation. By integrating real-time recognition and depth measurement from an RGB-D camera, the robot continuously adjusts its path in response to changes in the position of moving targets. Additionally, the integration of IoT enables real-time environmental updates and tracking. These three experimental validations collectively demonstrate the reasoning control capability, dynamic perception capability, and real-time adaptation capability of the LKPI framework. Experimental results show that LKPI eliminates dependence on LLM fine-tuning while enabling the efficient perception and control of real-time dynamic information in complex industrial environments, significantly enhancing the flexibility and task completion rate of robots in production processes. Future research will further extend this framework to applications and optimizations in multi-robot collaboration and long-range sensing. © 2025 by ASME.
