UR  - https://www.scopus.com/inward/record.uri?eid=2-s2.0-105011826322&doi=10.1109%2FICDSIS65355.2025.11070373&partnerID=40&md5=980bd005d650b241cb6741097ae2a576
AB  - Current multimodal question answering (QA) systems face challenges in cross-modal semantic alignment, discontinuity in reasoning chains, and outdated knowledge integration, especially in high-precision domains such as medical diagnosis. To this end, this study proposes a new LLM-based architecture. First, a multi-granular cross-modal contrastive learning module achieves fine-grained alignment of image-text semantics through region-phrase comparison and knowledge graph embedding. Next, a dynamic knowledge routing mechanism adaptively retrieves and injects external knowledge through gated attention. Finally, a multi-hop reasoning verification framework decomposes complex queries into sub-problems and generates intermediate hypotheses. Experiments on medical, scientific, and open-domain QA tasks show significant improvements in accuracy (87% for medical QA), factual consistency (13% error rate in complex scenarios), and multi-hop reasoning (88% accuracy for 2-hop tasks). The hierarchical design of the system effectively addresses cross-modal fusion and dynamic knowledge challenges, providing a robust solution for high-risk applications. Future work will focus on automated knowledge integration and human-in-the-loop optimization. © 2025 IEEE.
