TI  - Knowledge-Embedded Human-Machine Adaptation for Supporting Efficient Operations of Building Manufacturing Systems
PY  - 2024
SP  - 88
EP  - 97
DO  - 10.1061/9780784486122.010
UR  - https://www.scopus.com/inward/record.uri?eid=2-s2.0-105025358959&doi=10.1061%2F9780784486122.010&partnerID=40&md5=8f125b305cc2f52ab0d80ec2548d7ff8
AB  - Producing highly customizable building products involves human-machine interactions in dynamic and uncertain environments. Well-trained workers possess tacit knowledge of the process dynamics to achieve efficient manufacturing performance. However, such tacit knowledge is difficult to share and retain within organizations. The manufacturing workforce shortage has led to a need for context-aware decision-making support mechanisms for efficient operations. Two main challenges hinder the development of such systems. One challenge is the lack of data in modeling human-machine interaction dynamics. Another challenge is the lack of methods to interpret human-machine process patterns in changing contexts. We address these challenges by investigating the interplay between human operators and machines within dynamic production environments. Specifically, we first collected human-machine collaboration behaviors in different scenarios. A cognitive behavior decoding method interprets interactive behavior patterns between humans and machines. Simultaneously, we utilized behavior knowledge graph models to facilitate the transfer and reasoning of implicit knowledge related to efficient operations. Finally, we developed a large language model (LLM) augmented with a behavior knowledge graph to support decisions in operational tasks. The proposed methods were deployed and validated on an actual production line. The results demonstrated the efficacy of the proposed approach in knowledge capture and transfer for efficient operations. © ASCE.
